@end copying

@titlepage
@title cl-texinfo
@subtitle A Common Lisp Library for Generating Texinfo
@author 
@end titlepage

@contents

@node Top, Introduction, (dir), (dir)
@top cl-texinfo

cl-texinfo is a Common Lisp library that provides utilities for generating
Texinfo documentation programmatically. It offers macros and functions that
mirror Texinfo commands, making it easy to write documentation from within
Lisp code.

@node Introduction, Getting Started, Top, Top

@subsection Features

@itemize @bullet
@item Programmatic generation of Texinfo markup
@item Automatic escaping of special characters
@item Support for all major Texinfo commands
@item Macros for defining custom commands
@item Simple API for generating complete documents
@end itemize

@node Getting Started, Escaping Text, Introduction, Top
@chapter Getting Started

@section Installation

Load cl-texinfo in your Lisp image:

@example
(ql:quickload :texinfo)
@end example

@section Basic Usage

The library exports functions and macros corresponding to Texinfo commands.
Each command returns a string containing the generated Texinfo markup.

@example
(@chapter "Introduction")
@end example

This produces:

@example
@chapter Introduction
@end example

@section A Complete Example

Here is a simple example that generates a complete Texinfo document:

@lisp

(texinfo
  (@settitle "My Document")
  (@setfilename "my-document.info")
  (@node "Top" "Chapter 1" nil nil)
  (@top "My Document")
  (@chapter "Introduction")
  "This is the first chapter."
  (@bye))
@end lisp


@section Line Commands

Line commands produce output on a single line:

@lisp
(@@chapter "Introduction")
;; => "@@chapter Introduction\n"

(@@c "This is a comment")
;; => "@@c This is a comment\n"
@end lisp

@section Braced Commands

Braced commands wrap arguments in braces:

@lisp
(@@code "example")
;; => "@@code@{example@}"

(@@emph "important text")
;; => "@@emph@{important text@}"
@end lisp

Multiple arguments are separated by commas:

@lisp
(@@xref "Introduction" "see Introduction")
;; => "@@xref@{Introduction, see Introduction@}"
@end lisp

@section Block Commands

Block commands create environments that span multiple lines:

@lisp
(@@example ()
  (@@code "line 1")
  (@@code "line 2"))
;; => "@@example
;;      @@code@{line 1@}@@code@{line 2@}
;;     @@end example"
@end lisp

@node Document Structure, Text Formatting, Command Types, Top
@chapter Document Structure

@section Creating Nodes

Nodes are the fundamental navigation units in Texinfo:

@lisp
(@@node "Chapter One" "Chapter Two" "Top" "Top")
(@@chapter "First Chapter")
@end lisp

The @code{@node} function accepts up to four arguments:
@table @code
@item name
The node name (required)
@item next
The next node in sequence
@item previous
The previous node
@item up
The parent node
@end table

@section Chapter and Section Commands

Use chapter and section commands to structure your document:

@lisp
(@@chapter "Main Topic")
(@@section "Subtopic")
(@@subsection "Detail")
(@@subsubsection "Fine Detail")
@end lisp

@section Menus

Menus provide navigation within Info readers:

@lisp
(@@menu nil
  (menu-entry "Chapter 1" "chap1" "Introduction")
  (menu-entry "Chapter 2" "chap2" "Advanced Topics"))
@end lisp

@node Text Formatting, Cross References, Document Structure, Top
@chapter Text Formatting

@section Emphasis

@lisp
(@@emph "emphasized text")
(@@strong "strong emphasis")
(@@b "bold text")
(@@i "italic text")
@end lisp

@section Code and Samples

@lisp
(@@code "symbol-name")
(@@samp "sample text")
(@@var "variable")
(@@file "filename.lisp")
(@@command "ls -la")
(@@option "--verbose")
@end lisp

@section Quotations and Examples

Use block commands for longer passages:

@lisp
(@@quotation ()
  "This is a quoted passage.")
(@@example ()
  (@@code "(defun hello ()")
  (@@code "  (print \"Hello, World!\"))"))
@end lisp

@node Cross References, Lists and Tables, Text Formatting, Top
@chapter Cross References

@section Within a Document

@lisp
(@@xref "Node Name" "display text")
(@@ref "Node Name" "display text")
(@@anchor "anchor-name")
@end lisp

@section External References

@lisp
(@@url "https://example.com")
(@@uref "https://example.com" "Example Site")
(@@inforef "Node Name" "text" "manual-name")
@end lisp

@node Lists and Tables, Definition Commands, Cross References, Top
@chapter Lists and Tables

@section Itemize Lists

@lisp
(@@itemize (@@bullet)
  (@@item "First item")
  (@@item "Second item")
  (@@item "Third item"))
@end lisp

@section Enumerated Lists

@lisp
(@@enumerate (1)
  (@@item "Step one")
  (@@item "Step two")
  (@@item "Step three"))
@end lisp

@section Tables

@lisp
(@@table (@@code)
  (@@item "car")
  "Returns the first element of a list."
  (@@itemx "cdr")
  "Returns the rest of a list.")
@end lisp

@node Definition Commands, Rendering Output, Lists and Tables, Top
@chapter Definition Commands

Texinfo provides specialized commands for documenting code:

@section Variables

@lisp
(@@defvar "*standard-input*")
@end lisp

@section Functions

@lisp
(@@deffn "Function" "format" "stream control-string &rest arguments")
"Outputs formatted text to STREAM."
@end lisp

The library provides predefined definition commands:
@itemize @bullet
@item @code{@defvar}, @code{@defopt} - Variable definitions
@item @code{@deftypevar} - Typed variable definitions
@item @code{@deffn}, @code{@deftypefn} - Function definitions
@item @code{@defmacro} - Macro definitions
@item @code{@defvr}, @code{@deftypevr} - Generic definitions
@end itemize

@node Rendering Output, API Reference, Definition Commands, Top
@chapter Rendering Output

@section String Output

Use @code{texinfo} to generate a string:

@lisp
(texinfo
  (@@settitle "Document")
  (@@chapter "Content"))
@end lisp

@section File Output

Use @code{texinfo-to-file} to write directly to a file:

@lisp
(texinfo-to-file #p"output.texi"
  (@@settitle "My Document")
  (@@chapter "Introduction"))
@end lisp
